default&#xa0;defaultWritten evidence from defaultChris Hobbs, defaultRetired Metropolitan Police officer [CST0018]default&#xa0;
defaultI was born in London and have  lived here all my life. I come from a ‘police family’ and have relatives still serving within the force. My last ten years of service were spent working on Operation Trident related matters at UK and Jamaican airports. I have
default, however, extensive contacts throughout the Met which I have retained. I am aware of the frustrations of serving officers and their fears of expressing their concerns to senior managers for fear of repercussions. 
defaultI had personal experience of this when in
default June 2010, I wrote a letter intended for the press which, in addition to criticising Ken Clarke,  also referred extensively to crime figures. This included  the fact that damaging Met police gun crime figures had been excluded from the 
defaultMet’s
default annual report
default. I sought advice from the 
defaultMet’s
default Press Bureau and was told to submit it to them for scrutiny, which I did.  Despite that, I was hauled before my Chief Superintendent and accused of being 'unprofessional.' There was, so my Federation rep told me, a consider
defaultable body of opinion at the top of Scotland Yard that wanted me sacked. However they couldn't as I had formally submitted it internally first.
default13 months later I was forcibly retired albeit with a certificate of exemplary service.  My service record is beyo
defaultnd reproach and involved football related violence, Asian community tensions and international organised crime networks that blight the black community. Shortly after my retirement I was presented with a ceremonial sword and 
defaultsaropa
default (scarf) by the UK’s larg
defaultest Sikh temple. Despite this record  ‘dissent’ saw the end of my police career and this is the reason why ‘junior’ police officers will remain silent in the face of dubious police practices.
defaultThe officer, James Patrick is likely to be shown as an example o
defaultf what happens to officers who speak out. His decision to provide a submission to yourselves is extraordinary given the situation in which he finds himself. His book, ‘The Rest is Silence’ is in fact a restrained but disturbing critique of the police refor
defaultm process. He does not advocate any form of militant action by front line officers, in fact quite the reverse. By forensic examination based on fact, he casts doubt on the process and the motives of those responsible for it. The 
defaultMet’s
default  Commissioner  appear
defaults determined to send a signal to his rank and file that ‘rocking the boat’ will have consequences.  
defaultBelow is my submission in respect of crime figures. They are an amalgam of views from front line serving officers who are concerned at the machinations of 
defaultmanagers in respect of crime figures. There is also comment in respect of the Crime Survey for England and Wales which is also used by police forces to support their mantra of falling crime. 
